objectives.en:
The course is meant to:
- introduce the concept of biopolitics, its vocabulary and theoretical background;
- demonstrate the cognitive potential of biopolitics as an explanatory tool for a variety of contemporary political, social and cultural issues;
- explicate the possibilities of using biopolitics for comparative policy analysis.

description.et:
Assessment is differentiated according to the following criteria:
E - the presentation is, in general, in compliance with the requirements and correct; references to sources of information are minimal; the elements of analysis and independent interpretation are there; the coverage of the subject is, in general, logical, but the connections between elements are full of gaps;
D - the form of the presentation is in compliance with the requirements and, in general, correct; references to the extant literatures are random, but relevant; the analysis and independent interpretation is understandable, but at times insecure; the coverage of the subject is fragmented
C - the form of the presentation is in compliance with the requirements; references are relevant and sufficient; analytical connections and interpretations are proper and there is certainty in creating connections; the treatment of the subject 
is logical, but there are some weaknesses from the point of view of the general argument;
B - the form of the presentation is very good; the choice, amount and association of references with the text is clear; thorough analysis of references; bold interpretation based on connections; the treatment of the subject as a whole is logical and smooth;
A - the form is excellent; the choice, amount and association of references with the text is creative; the depth of the analysis and the level of independent interpretation is remarkable; the connections are thorough-going and creative; the treatment of the subject is innovative and logical; the text is a remarkable achievement on the whole
